100mm segments and 3 clusters¶

In [5]:
plt.figure(1, figsize=(12,6))
cluster_analysis.plot_n_nearest(seg_length = 100, n_clusters = 3, n_nearest_neighbours = n_nearest_neighbours, root_path = root_path)

Looking at this, it seems that the silhouette score is not a great way to determine the optimum number of clusters. I would say here there is definitely a 3 geometric shape that has been determined. That being said, just because we have found a shape it doesn't mean that there is a particularly strategy being applied. I imagine that better evidence of a strategy is a pattern that is repeated.

Possible reasons why the silhouette values might be poor at identifying an optimum number of clusters are, because the features used either can't capture the strategy or they are finding patterns that are not easily observable by eye.

Given that kmeans found what we believe to be an additional cluster I think it makes sense to check for a possible 4th.

100mm segments and 4 clusters¶

In [6]:

I think what we are seeing here is less clear now. ClusterID 0 and ClusterID 2 have considerable similarities and while clusterID does have some common traits across each plotted segment, they are less consistent.

Let's look at some longer segment lengths now.

Before we do though, its probably worth making the point, that given the way the experiment was conducted, I think its unlikely that we will see consistent repetive patterns that occur over longer periods, at least patterns such as those that move around the edge, because the bee is reacting to a stimulus at regular intervals that disrupt the pattern.

Conclusion¶

I believe there are several candidates for a good length and number of clusters. These are:

  • 150mm & 5 clusters
  • 300mm & 2 clusters
  • 200mm & 4 clusters
  • 250mm & 4 clusters

Although there are clear distinctions between segments in the shorter length segments, I don't believe they contain enough information to deem them strategies.

The 300mm & 2 clusters initially might not seem like a great choice since we aren't identifying many types of behaviour. That being said, I think that bee behaviour is going to be more simplistic than the rodent behaviour and so perhaps this is the best we can do. There's also a chance that when we are find more clusters for other segment lengths, what we are finding is just regular movement patterns that don't indicate a strategy. This line of thinking however, is far from conclusive.

While the silhouette score has helped to guide the process, here we can see that using it blindly particularly if we wanted to automate the process, will most likely lead to a less optimum clustering regime.
